1
00:00:20,220 --> 00:00:22,518
"RONALDS BROTHERS PRODUCTIONS"

2
00:00:24,524 --> 00:00:28,187
"DARRELL HAMMOND"

3
00:00:29,362 --> 00:00:33,628
"STEVE BURNS"

4
00:00:37,370 --> 00:00:39,998
"DAVE FOLEY"

5
00:00:42,809 --> 00:00:46,575
"AMY DAVIDSON"

6
00:01:09,436 --> 00:01:10,027
Morning, Otto.

7
00:01:10,103 --> 00:01:10,797
Good morning.

8
00:01:10,937 --> 00:01:11,995
It was a long meeting, huh?

9
00:01:12,072 --> 00:01:14,370
Yeah. I don't think lunch
will ever get here.

10
00:01:14,474 --> 00:01:15,065
You hungry?

11
00:01:15,775 --> 00:01:16,434
Little bit.

12
00:01:18,044 --> 00:01:18,703
Morning, sir.

13
00:01:19,145 --> 00:01:19,770
Morning, Otto.

14
00:01:23,483 --> 00:01:24,245
Good morning, Otto.

15
00:01:24,517 --> 00:01:27,748
Good morning, Henry.
Turner wants to see me.

16
00:01:28,054 --> 00:01:28,748
He does?

17
00:01:28,822 --> 00:01:29,288
Yeah.

18
00:01:29,355 --> 00:01:30,049
What about?

19
00:01:30,290 --> 00:01:31,052
I'll let you know.

20
00:01:31,291 --> 00:01:32,019
Alright.

21
00:01:33,193 --> 00:01:38,893
You bet. Whatever you need to
fix the situation is great.

22
00:01:40,300 --> 00:01:41,528
Hi, you wanted to see me sir?

23
00:01:41,668 --> 00:01:42,692
Yeah. Sit.

24
00:01:43,236 --> 00:01:45,033
Absolutely,
I'm putting one of my top guys on it.

25
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:50,376
Yes. Doug, could you give us
'til Wednesday on this thing?

26
00:01:50,443 --> 00:01:52,877
It's starting out to
be one of those days.

27
00:01:55,815 --> 00:01:56,782
Sit down.

28
00:01:58,118 --> 00:02:00,518
Super. You have my personal guarantee.

29
00:02:01,688 --> 00:02:02,814
Okay, thanks again.

30
00:02:05,492 --> 00:02:08,893
Otto, I need your help.
And we don't have a lot of time.

31
00:02:09,262 --> 00:02:10,286
What the hell's going on, Turner?

32
00:02:10,497 --> 00:02:11,987
It's the proposal.

33
00:02:12,065 --> 00:02:15,057
The initiative for Donigan Corp.
It's a mess.

34
00:02:15,135 --> 00:02:19,970
Oh, I, I mean,
um, what, what happened to Mike?

35
00:02:21,541 --> 00:02:23,099
I apologize. I meant to clean that up.

36
00:02:23,510 --> 00:02:25,501
What I need you to do, in a nutshell,

37
00:02:25,712 --> 00:02:29,204
is rewrite the Donigan Initiative
by Tuesday.

38
00:02:29,349 --> 00:02:31,715
Mike's version
wasn't quite up to par.

39
00:02:31,851 --> 00:02:32,818
Wasn't up to par?

40
00:02:32,886 --> 00:02:33,545
No.

41
00:02:34,521 --> 00:02:36,716
So, so you killed him?

42
00:02:36,789 --> 00:02:39,917
Oh, no, lord no.

43
00:02:40,026 --> 00:02:42,426
That had nothing to do
with why I killed him.

44
00:02:42,929 --> 00:02:46,490
Then, why did you do it?

45
00:02:46,633 --> 00:02:49,500
Observe. Use reason.

46
00:02:50,069 --> 00:02:52,128
There's a wooden stake in his heart.

47
00:02:53,239 --> 00:02:55,673
What logical conclusion
could you draw from that, Otto?

48
00:02:57,677 --> 00:02:58,609
Mike was a vampire.

49
00:03:01,114 --> 00:03:03,947
Now, the intro and
the summary really aren't that bad,

50
00:03:04,017 --> 00:03:06,076
but they definitely need to
be punched up just a little bit.

51
00:03:06,152 --> 00:03:08,552
What makes you think
Mike was a vampire?

52
00:03:08,888 --> 00:03:12,051
Otto, when you've been
in management as long as I have,

53
00:03:12,125 --> 00:03:13,490
you recognize the signs.

54
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:14,758
What signs?

55
00:03:14,994 --> 00:03:18,862
You know, sleeps in a coffin,
uh, drinks blood to survive.

56
00:03:18,932 --> 00:03:21,730
Can't go out in the sunlight,
aversion to garlic.

57
00:03:21,834 --> 00:03:23,859
Awkwardness in social situations.

58
00:03:23,937 --> 00:03:26,201
When did Mike start drinking blood?

59
00:03:26,739 --> 00:03:29,537
It's hard to say.
It could be hundreds of years.

60
00:03:30,143 --> 00:03:33,408
Have you ever seen Mike drink blood?

61
00:03:33,479 --> 00:03:35,709
He had some on his shirt
when he came in here.

62
00:03:35,782 --> 00:03:37,750
Must have dripped
while he was feasting on

63
00:03:37,817 --> 00:03:40,513
what I can only assume
was his final victim.

64
00:03:41,054 --> 00:03:41,952
Where on his shirt?

65
00:03:42,055 --> 00:03:43,317
It's right there on the front.

66
00:03:45,491 --> 00:03:50,952
Oh, well, I guess you got
to take my word for it.

67
00:03:51,731 --> 00:03:52,459
Turner...

68
00:03:52,532 --> 00:03:56,593
Hmm?
There's no such thing as vampires.

69
00:03:56,669 --> 00:03:59,229
Then how come the only way
I could kill him

70
00:03:59,305 --> 00:04:01,330
was to drive
that wooden stake through his heart?

71
00:04:01,407 --> 00:04:03,170
Did you try any other ways?

72
00:04:03,476 --> 00:04:06,343
No. How naive do you think I am?

73
00:04:06,679 --> 00:04:07,873
He's a vampire.

74
00:04:08,147 --> 00:04:11,139
A vampire requires
a wooden stake through the heart.

75
00:04:11,217 --> 00:04:14,209
You wouldn't eat spaghetti
with a skateboard, would you, Otto?

76
00:04:14,520 --> 00:04:15,350
What?

77
00:04:15,421 --> 00:04:17,685
It's a simple question
to which the answer is 'no.'

78
00:04:17,757 --> 00:04:19,782
You wouldn't eat spaghetti
with a skateboard

79
00:04:19,859 --> 00:04:22,657
because it's the wrong tool
for the job.

80
00:04:23,296 --> 00:04:24,593
Mike wasn't a vampire.

81
00:04:24,664 --> 00:04:25,460
If that's true,

82
00:04:25,531 --> 00:04:29,058
then why did he recoil in terror
when I shoved a crucifix in his face?

83
00:04:29,402 --> 00:04:30,835
He was Jewish.

84
00:04:30,903 --> 00:04:34,566
Otto, I would love to sit around here
and talk about religion with you,

85
00:04:34,807 --> 00:04:37,469
but the employee handbook
strictly forbids indulging

86
00:04:37,543 --> 00:04:40,535
in such volatile topics
of conversation in the workplace.

87
00:04:40,680 --> 00:04:42,409
It upsets some people.

88
00:04:42,815 --> 00:04:44,407
Now, if you'll excuse me,

89
00:04:44,851 --> 00:04:47,752
I need to sort through
how we're going to replace Mike.

90
00:04:48,221 --> 00:04:51,918
Damn his vampirism, today of all days.

91
00:04:52,859 --> 00:04:54,986
Uh,
two bullet points for your to do list:

92
00:04:55,395 --> 00:04:58,330
rewrite the Donigan initiative
by two PM on Tuesday.

93
00:04:58,564 --> 00:05:04,230
Incinerate the demon Mike's unearthly
husk in roughly, uh, one hour.

94
00:05:24,624 --> 00:05:25,454
Oh, guys?

95
00:05:29,062 --> 00:05:29,926
We're screwed.

96
00:05:30,463 --> 00:05:34,160
Jeff, you might want to clean that up.

97
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:45,004
"NETHERBEAST INCORPORATED"

98
00:06:14,540 --> 00:06:17,634
I'm Otto Granberry,
and I'm 108 years old.

99
00:06:17,977 --> 00:06:21,811
This moment began one of the darkest
chapters in Berm-Tech's long history.

100
00:06:21,914 --> 00:06:22,903
It could have been worse,

101
00:06:23,015 --> 00:06:25,950
like if Mike Yarrow had been
a likeable guy, for instance.

102
00:06:26,018 --> 00:06:27,349
"44 Minutes Ago."
But he wasn't.

103
00:06:27,420 --> 00:06:28,751
It makes me feel better for Turner

104
00:06:28,821 --> 00:06:31,491
that the person
he killed seemed entirely deserving.

105
00:06:31,491 --> 00:06:35,257
Yeah, Dow, that's just
what you need is another muffin.

106
00:06:35,328 --> 00:06:36,795
Hey, come on, Mike.

107
00:06:38,030 --> 00:06:39,622
Pad that ass, big boy.

108
00:06:42,969 --> 00:06:43,526
A-hole.

109
00:06:43,603 --> 00:06:47,095
Considering what happened next,
Turner must have thought the same.

110
00:06:47,173 --> 00:06:49,733
I've never understood
why we've got this thing down here.

111
00:06:50,042 --> 00:06:53,068
It seems so incredibly dangerous
in a building this old.

112
00:06:54,313 --> 00:06:58,340
Just following FERC regulations
regarding sensitive paperwork.

113
00:06:58,951 --> 00:07:02,785
I personally feel it's much more
thorough than a paper shredder.

114
00:07:02,989 --> 00:07:05,685
Oh. I won't argue the point, Otto.

115
00:07:05,892 --> 00:07:07,484
All hands meeting, ten minutes,

116
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:10,620
assemble everyone in the meadow,
if you would, please.

117
00:07:11,230 --> 00:07:11,855
Will do.

118
00:07:12,799 --> 00:07:15,461
Between you and me,
I'm beginning to think

119
00:07:15,535 --> 00:07:17,526
that Mike was just a low-level operative in

120
00:07:17,603 --> 00:07:20,595
what appears to be
a large network of the cursed

121
00:07:20,673 --> 00:07:22,937
and undead here
at Berm-Tech Industries.

122
00:07:27,113 --> 00:07:29,911
And I can assure you that
my actions were completely warranted

123
00:07:29,982 --> 00:07:33,975
given the complex set of circumstances
involved, visa vi, his vampirism.

124
00:07:34,754 --> 00:07:38,246
But rest assured, I acted
in the best interest of this company,

125
00:07:38,324 --> 00:07:40,292
as well as your personal safety.

126
00:07:40,693 --> 00:07:43,560
Personal safety, that's key.

127
00:07:44,363 --> 00:07:47,764
Our Zero-Tolerance Program will be
expanded to include this issue.

128
00:07:47,834 --> 00:07:51,964
Eating co-workers, or any nonaffiliated
personnel in accordance with the...

129
00:07:52,038 --> 00:07:55,701
Hearing Turner toss around the term
vampire is so foreign to my ears.

130
00:07:56,876 --> 00:07:59,436
He's hated that word for
as long as anyone's known him.

131
00:07:59,645 --> 00:08:01,112
Yeah, Turner's one of us.

132
00:08:02,248 --> 00:08:06,184
So this is clearly the retardations
talking, which I'll get to shortly.

133
00:08:06,252 --> 00:08:07,954
...vampires, they win.

134
00:08:07,954 --> 00:08:09,945
And vampires shouldn't be winners.

135
00:08:10,223 --> 00:08:11,986
That's not to say
that Mike was a loser.

136
00:08:12,692 --> 00:08:16,788
Maybe he didn't have a choice
in his bloodsucking peculiarities.

137
00:08:16,996 --> 00:08:20,557
Perhaps more accurately,
Mike was an un-winner.

138
00:08:21,334 --> 00:08:25,634
By way of illustration,
a vampire walks into a bar.

139
00:08:26,539 --> 00:08:30,532
Okay, let's get this whole
vampire debate out of the way.

140
00:08:30,943 --> 00:08:33,173
First of all, we're not vampires.

141
00:08:33,546 --> 00:08:37,517
That's a whole media thing invented
by Gram Stoker to sell books.

142
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,712
We don't have fangs,
and we don't fly.

143
00:08:39,886 --> 00:08:41,649
And yes, we have reflections.

144
00:08:42,622 --> 00:08:46,251
Vampire makes us sound like,
well, monsters.

145
00:08:47,159 --> 00:08:50,322
In the Middle Ages we were referred
to as 'Nether Beasts,'

146
00:08:50,796 --> 00:08:52,388
but we prefer 'Nether Folk.'

147
00:08:52,865 --> 00:08:57,165
We're really normal people
with a slight birth defect.

148
00:08:57,503 --> 00:09:00,768
The heart's the thing.
It's what make us special.

149
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:03,308
We have an odd growth on our hearts.

150
00:09:03,643 --> 00:09:06,237
It looks like a gristly, veiny clump.

151
00:09:06,746 --> 00:09:10,477
This clump secretes an enzyme when
someone is faced with an unnatural death.

152
00:09:10,816 --> 00:09:12,306
Some sort of body trauma.

153
00:09:12,985 --> 00:09:15,453
You'll recover as long as
your heart's not destroyed.

154
00:09:15,521 --> 00:09:17,113
And you're willing to feast.

155
00:09:17,957 --> 00:09:19,891
Which brings up a naive notion...

156
00:09:19,959 --> 00:09:21,688
...drinks blood to survive.

157
00:09:21,928 --> 00:09:23,452
Oh, if it were only that easy.

158
00:09:23,596 --> 00:09:26,064
Blood's great and all,
but blood alone won't do it.

159
00:09:26,532 --> 00:09:29,228
No, we need human flesh as well.

160
00:09:29,769 --> 00:09:33,136
Through various connections
we keep a steady supply of choice,

161
00:09:33,205 --> 00:09:35,366
recently-deceased people in inventory.

162
00:09:37,977 --> 00:09:39,444
See, we're not beasts.

163
00:09:39,779 --> 00:09:42,407
Long gone are the days
of murder and mayhem.

164
00:09:42,481 --> 00:09:44,039
We enjoy human flesh and blood,

165
00:09:44,350 --> 00:09:47,376
but try not to eat
any more than we need to.

166
00:09:47,753 --> 00:09:49,550
And in the hands of the master chef,

167
00:09:49,622 --> 00:09:52,056
there are infinite ways
to prepare human flesh.

168
00:09:52,658 --> 00:09:55,889
Once the body has experienced
the initial secretion, you're set.

169
00:09:56,062 --> 00:09:58,189
No disease, and wounds heal quickly.

170
00:09:58,598 --> 00:09:59,895
That doesn't mean
limbs will grow back,

171
00:09:59,966 --> 00:10:02,526
or your skin will mend flawlessly.

172
00:10:03,102 --> 00:10:04,865
It's about survival.

173
00:10:05,404 --> 00:10:06,803
Repairing life functions.

174
00:10:07,340 --> 00:10:08,034
Not magic.

175
00:10:08,307 --> 00:10:09,433
In our golden age,

176
00:10:09,508 --> 00:10:11,032
when blood flowed like wine,

177
00:10:11,177 --> 00:10:15,045
and flesh flowed like,
well, much thicker wine,

178
00:10:15,381 --> 00:10:18,873
we learned that our existence
is reliant on a rare mineral

179
00:10:18,951 --> 00:10:20,646
we call 'Nether Stone.'

180
00:10:21,320 --> 00:10:24,346
It's securely locked and
hidden away here at Berm-Tech,

181
00:10:24,423 --> 00:10:26,220
and it's vital to our survival.

182
00:10:26,626 --> 00:10:30,460
Nether Stone radiates and enriches
the enzyme in our heart.

183
00:10:30,896 --> 00:10:32,761
As long as we're within a mile of it,

184
00:10:32,832 --> 00:10:36,063
and continue to feast,
we can live healthy lives.

185
00:10:36,669 --> 00:10:39,297
As healthy as you can be eating flesh,
I guess.

186
00:10:40,873 --> 00:10:43,433
And we need to put this behind us.

187
00:10:43,509 --> 00:10:45,670
As the representative
from Landry Ventures

188
00:10:45,745 --> 00:10:48,441
will be arriving shortly after lunch.

189
00:10:52,685 --> 00:10:56,212
Oops.
I spoiled my surprise, didn't I?

190
00:10:56,789 --> 00:11:00,725
Well, I will say that his presence
here is a progressive step

191
00:11:00,793 --> 00:11:04,251
towards moving Berm-Tech firmly
into the 21st Century.

192
00:11:04,430 --> 00:11:07,831
But don't worry,
none of you will be affected directly,

193
00:11:07,900 --> 00:11:12,496
although in fairness I should say that
all of you will be affected somewhat.

194
00:11:13,372 --> 00:11:17,274
Once we heard that an outside visitor,
a 'first lifer' was coming,

195
00:11:18,244 --> 00:11:20,007
we went into scramble mode.

196
00:11:20,513 --> 00:11:21,878
Cleaning, hiding, covering up.

197
00:11:25,951 --> 00:11:28,511
Except for an occasional
maintenance person of civic inspector,

198
00:11:28,587 --> 00:11:30,282
we don't allow visitors.

199
00:11:31,057 --> 00:11:33,218
The lobby is manned
by Jewel Hightower.

200
00:11:33,292 --> 00:11:35,385
Maybe 'manned' is the wrong word.

201
00:11:35,494 --> 00:11:37,621
There are no windows to the outside,

202
00:11:37,697 --> 00:11:40,757
there's a small office where we meet
with our various suppliers and customers.

203
00:11:40,933 --> 00:11:42,400
Two framed photos hang on the wall.

204
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:45,561
One of Alexander Graham Bell,
and his associates,

205
00:11:45,638 --> 00:11:47,572
and one of President James Garfield.

206
00:11:47,873 --> 00:11:49,602
The elevator to
the office floors lies

207
00:11:49,675 --> 00:11:52,576
behind a pair of
admittedly unattractive doors.

208
00:11:52,645 --> 00:11:54,169
Few get beyond the chartreuse doors
of Berm-Tech.

209
00:11:54,280 --> 00:11:57,772
We began as a subsidiary of the
Bell Telephone Company in Baltimore,

210
00:11:57,850 --> 00:12:03,288
Maryland in 1886.
Alexander Graham Bell himself arranged it

211
00:12:03,355 --> 00:12:05,414
as a favor
to President Garfield.

212
00:12:05,491 --> 00:12:06,924
But I'll get to that later.

213
00:12:07,193 --> 00:12:09,457
We had to move around a lot
in the early days,

214
00:12:09,528 --> 00:12:12,122
when we'd find ourselves
on the verge of being unmasked.

215
00:12:12,331 --> 00:12:15,823
We eventually got 'low profile'
concept down pat.

216
00:12:16,035 --> 00:12:19,163
Since the beginning
we've manufactured telephones.

217
00:12:19,672 --> 00:12:22,732
But in the last 20 years,
we're more into farming out the work,

218
00:12:22,942 --> 00:12:25,706
coordinating the assembly of
telecommunications components.

219
00:12:26,645 --> 00:12:30,137
Anyway, after lunch, Berm-Tech's
managers gathered together.

220
00:12:30,249 --> 00:12:32,877
This group consists of
our number three guy, Henry Welby.

221
00:12:33,352 --> 00:12:36,412
He died in 1863
as a Confederate soldier.

222
00:12:36,589 --> 00:12:37,419
Bunyan Pritchett.

223
00:12:38,190 --> 00:12:40,954
He was shot with
a Gatling gun forty-four times.

224
00:12:41,227 --> 00:12:43,320
And our second in command,
Rebecca Sibley,

225
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:46,360
gunned down on the arm
of a gangster in 1926.

226
00:12:46,432 --> 00:12:48,127
A productivity consultant?

227
00:12:48,267 --> 00:12:50,064
Why on earth would
he hire one of those?

228
00:12:50,836 --> 00:12:51,962
Why would he kill Mike?

229
00:12:52,471 --> 00:12:54,530
I mean, we all know
it's the retardations,

230
00:12:54,607 --> 00:12:56,575
even Dr. Berman says so.

231
00:12:56,942 --> 00:13:00,173
Or, do you still have a problem
with that, Henry?

232
00:13:00,546 --> 00:13:01,137
Yeah, sorry.

233
00:13:01,380 --> 00:13:05,111
The retardations.
Not a very P.C. term, I'll admit.

234
00:13:05,251 --> 00:13:06,741
But it's been around a while.

235
00:13:07,753 --> 00:13:10,620
Think of it as Alzheimer's
for vampires.

236
00:13:10,823 --> 00:13:11,790
Nether Folk, I'm sorry.

237
00:13:12,525 --> 00:13:16,017
Except it's onset is much quicker,
within a few days.

238
00:13:16,228 --> 00:13:18,492
And the memories aren't gone,
just dormant.

239
00:13:19,031 --> 00:13:22,364
Advanced age is a factor,
but it can strike any of us.

240
00:13:22,568 --> 00:13:26,436
Turner is 191 years old,
which is pretty old.

241
00:13:26,872 --> 00:13:31,332
In most cases, once the retardation
set in, it's over.

242
00:13:31,410 --> 00:13:36,848
But occasionally they reverse themselves
naturally, resulting in normal behavior.

243
00:13:36,916 --> 00:13:39,407
I guess that's what we were
all hoping for with Turner.

244
00:13:39,752 --> 00:13:42,380
Look,
no one wants to say anything about it,

245
00:13:42,454 --> 00:13:45,446
but perhaps it's time to enjoin
Turner to the greater number.

246
00:13:45,524 --> 00:13:47,219
No, it's too early for that, Bunyan.

247
00:13:48,227 --> 00:13:50,889
But from a risk-management
standpoint it makes sense.

248
00:13:50,963 --> 00:13:52,828
No, Henry's right, it's too early.

249
00:13:52,998 --> 00:13:54,727
Let's see
if the retardations reverse.

250
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:56,267
Yes, remember Rafe Costello?

251
00:13:56,569 --> 00:13:58,400
He reversed in the second week.

252
00:13:58,771 --> 00:14:00,796
That was 25 years ago, Henry.

253
00:14:00,873 --> 00:14:02,204
Well so what? So what?

254
00:14:02,274 --> 00:14:05,038
You know, we, we put a couple
of guys on to shadow him,

255
00:14:05,211 --> 00:14:06,906
and, uh, he'll be no trouble at all.

256
00:14:06,979 --> 00:14:10,745
Okay, barring an emergency situation,
one more week. Agreed?

257
00:14:10,850 --> 00:14:11,782
Agreed.

258
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:37,673
He brings 22 years of productivity
consulting experience to us,

259
00:14:38,310 --> 00:14:41,507
and good lord, you've been
at this a while, haven't you Steven?

260
00:14:43,482 --> 00:14:48,886
Hello. I know what you're
all thinking, 'he's a cost-cutter,'

261
00:14:49,021 --> 00:14:53,515
which means downsizing, subsequent
layoffs and pink slips, right?

262
00:14:53,692 --> 00:14:55,751
In the interest of full disclosure,

263
00:14:55,895 --> 00:14:57,920
that wasn't exactly
what we were thinking.

264
00:14:58,130 --> 00:14:59,290
This guy's got to go.

265
00:14:59,798 --> 00:15:02,358
What the hell was Turner thinking?

266
00:15:02,434 --> 00:15:04,061
This guy could ruin everything.

267
00:15:04,303 --> 00:15:05,668
He looks delicious.

268
00:15:05,738 --> 00:15:07,171
With a baked potato.

269
00:15:07,239 --> 00:15:08,536
A few collared greens.

270
00:15:08,607 --> 00:15:14,375
Don't worry. I have never once
recommended layoffs or pink slips.

271
00:15:14,446 --> 00:15:18,405
Especially for a company that's been
in business as long as Berm-Tech.

272
00:15:18,951 --> 00:15:24,514
And I'm convinced that each and
every one of you is a capable employee.

273
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:28,117
Capable is key.

274
00:15:28,794 --> 00:15:34,960
Key.
It's about procedure not personnel.

275
00:15:35,034 --> 00:15:39,266
So don't worry,
you'll hardly feel a thing.

276
00:15:39,705 --> 00:15:41,673
And this is my go-to guy, Henry Welby.

277
00:15:42,174 --> 00:15:43,436
And this Otto Granberry.

278
00:15:43,842 --> 00:15:45,673
A Team-Lead under Henry.

279
00:15:46,612 --> 00:15:48,341
It's nice to meet you,
looking forward to the work.

280
00:15:48,414 --> 00:15:50,439
And Henry.

281
00:15:50,516 --> 00:15:51,505
Steven.

282
00:15:51,583 --> 00:15:52,709
I've heard a lot of things.

283
00:15:52,785 --> 00:15:55,151
I'm hoping to rely heavily
on your expertise.

284
00:15:55,354 --> 00:15:58,346
Well, of course.
Any, anything I can do to help.

285
00:15:58,691 --> 00:16:00,818
We were about to take a little tour
of the facilities,

286
00:16:00,893 --> 00:16:04,659
but Rebecca has asked that Henry
and I have a short powwow,

287
00:16:04,730 --> 00:16:09,064
so I was hoping that Otto would
play tour guide for a little while.

288
00:16:09,401 --> 00:16:09,958
Sure.

289
00:16:10,469 --> 00:16:12,664
That sounds great, but FYI, Turner,

290
00:16:13,372 --> 00:16:15,932
powwow could be
construed as offensive.

291
00:16:16,008 --> 00:16:17,669
Really? That's good to know.

292
00:16:18,043 --> 00:16:20,978
I guess that's why we pay you
the heap big wampum.

293
00:16:23,048 --> 00:16:23,571
Shall we?

294
00:16:23,882 --> 00:16:28,012
As luck would have it, the first
employee on our tour was Emmitt Neely.

295
00:16:28,220 --> 00:16:29,380
Our director of security.

296
00:16:29,588 --> 00:16:31,988
Emmitt,
I'd like you to meet Steven Landry.

297
00:16:32,825 --> 00:16:33,951
It's nice to meet you, Emmitt.

298
00:16:34,026 --> 00:16:35,288
Likewise, my man.

299
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:40,966
Hey, I like those pants.

300
00:16:41,033 --> 00:16:41,692
Yeah?

301
00:16:42,134 --> 00:16:44,466
I had a pair of those back
when they were all the rage.

302
00:16:44,737 --> 00:16:46,102
They're back again, Steven.

303
00:16:46,438 --> 00:16:48,167
Like a runaway train, they're back.

304
00:16:48,240 --> 00:16:49,901
Oh,
I don't know about a runaway train.

305
00:16:49,975 --> 00:16:51,306
Like a runaway train.

306
00:16:54,646 --> 00:16:55,635
That's terrific.

307
00:16:58,283 --> 00:17:03,812
Uh, if there's ever an emergency,
we have an on-site medical facility.

308
00:17:03,889 --> 00:17:05,324
Would you like to meet Dr. Berman?

309
00:17:05,324 --> 00:17:06,552
We don't have to do that today.

310
00:17:06,692 --> 00:17:08,683
Okay. Let's...

311
00:17:10,729 --> 00:17:13,220
It's just ten days, Henry.

312
00:17:13,665 --> 00:17:15,826
Yeah, but it's very destructive,
and expensive.

313
00:17:16,435 --> 00:17:19,199
You're taking
the 40 thousand foot view here, Henry.

314
00:17:19,271 --> 00:17:21,102
You got to get granular
with this thing.

315
00:17:21,173 --> 00:17:23,164
Money isn't the issue here.

316
00:17:23,976 --> 00:17:25,876
We never had to
worry much about money.

317
00:17:25,978 --> 00:17:28,845
Hell, we bought into AT&T
at four cents a share.

318
00:17:29,748 --> 00:17:32,581
But we've never needed
that to prop up the bottom line. Never.

319
00:17:33,018 --> 00:17:36,385
As Turner likes to say,
'we're a well-oiled machine.'

320
00:17:36,455 --> 00:17:39,151
You always say
we're a well-oiled machine.

321
00:17:39,224 --> 00:17:40,919
Yeah, well it's been brought
to my attention

322
00:17:40,993 --> 00:17:43,484
that we're getting
a little squeaky around here lately.

323
00:17:43,629 --> 00:17:44,391
Who said that?

324
00:17:44,463 --> 00:17:45,657
It's not important.

325
00:17:45,731 --> 00:17:47,528
Just let him finish, Rebecca.

326
00:17:47,666 --> 00:17:53,536
Ten days. Look, this is going to work,
or my name isn't...

327
00:18:03,682 --> 00:18:05,513
Then we stopped in to see Bunyan.

328
00:18:06,585 --> 00:18:11,113
Wow. Now that's a conversation piece.

329
00:18:11,990 --> 00:18:13,082
That's my dog, Jeeves.

330
00:18:13,392 --> 00:18:16,793
I won a sweepstakes, got a gift
certificate to a taxidermy shop.

331
00:18:17,229 --> 00:18:18,423
It was my first time.

332
00:18:19,064 --> 00:18:24,627
How long were you with Jeeves before
you had him mounted for posterity?

333
00:18:24,703 --> 00:18:28,662
Oh, only a couple of days. I bought
him especially for the occasion.

334
00:18:29,975 --> 00:18:30,805
Fantastic.

335
00:18:31,810 --> 00:18:36,213
For the first time in decades I was
seeing my co-workers through fresh eyes.

336
00:18:36,915 --> 00:18:39,782
Which, evidently,
isn't the best way to see them.

337
00:18:43,055 --> 00:18:44,750
You have a wonderful evening, Jewel.

338
00:18:53,065 --> 00:18:55,499
The consultant has left the building.

339
00:18:55,767 --> 00:18:58,861
I repeat,
the consultant has left the building.

340
00:18:59,571 --> 00:19:03,371
Now, at the risk of trampling
on vampire mythology once again...

341
00:19:03,742 --> 00:19:05,607
You know, sleeps in a coffin?

342
00:19:05,677 --> 00:19:07,338
We don't sleep in coffins.

343
00:19:07,412 --> 00:19:09,778
In fact we sleep
in quite comfortable beds,

344
00:19:09,882 --> 00:19:11,543
with fresh sheets every week.

345
00:19:11,850 --> 00:19:13,249
Ugly sheets, but fresh.

346
00:19:13,385 --> 00:19:16,877
The carpet is
a lovely blueberry vomit weave.

347
00:19:17,789 --> 00:19:19,416
The lamps are hideous.

348
00:19:19,591 --> 00:19:22,890
And the curtains look like they date
back to the Roosevelt Administration.

349
00:19:23,262 --> 00:19:24,729
Not the new Roosevelt, either.

350
00:19:25,164 --> 00:19:27,428
We live in the top five floors
of Berm-Tech.

351
00:19:28,233 --> 00:19:30,667
We have 70 rooms,
and only 61 employees.

352
00:19:31,036 --> 00:19:32,731
That gives us some freedom.

353
00:19:32,971 --> 00:19:35,098
The enzyme renders us sterile
and infertile,

354
00:19:35,440 --> 00:19:37,601
it's like shooting blanks
at moving targets.

355
00:19:38,177 --> 00:19:40,145
We also have
an imperviousness to disease.

356
00:19:40,979 --> 00:19:42,571
So we can be a randy lot.

357
00:19:43,448 --> 00:19:46,440
So, no, we don't sleep in coffins.
There you go.

358
00:19:57,262 --> 00:19:58,194
Is somebody there?

359
00:20:06,905 --> 00:20:07,997
Is that you, Waxy?

360
00:20:08,607 --> 00:20:11,474
With some of
your late night pornography?

361
00:20:13,712 --> 00:20:15,441
Telly's all yours, old man.

362
00:20:16,281 --> 00:20:17,942
But you better be wearing pants.

363
00:20:28,727 --> 00:20:31,594
Most people think of Thanksgiving
as the start of the holiday season,

364
00:20:31,763 --> 00:20:34,027
but we Nether Folk start a week
or two earlier,

365
00:20:34,499 --> 00:20:35,989
on James Garfield's birthday.

366
00:20:36,935 --> 00:20:39,403
That guy eating with us is my pal,
Dan Paraffin.

367
00:20:39,638 --> 00:20:41,629
Everyone's always known him
as Waxy Dan.

368
00:20:42,174 --> 00:20:45,837
Well, actually nobody's always
been known as anything around here.

369
00:20:46,011 --> 00:20:48,536
Early on we thought our suppliers
might get suspicious

370
00:20:48,614 --> 00:20:51,344
if we hung onto our first life names
for too long.

371
00:20:51,717 --> 00:20:54,743
So every ten years or so,
we change them.

372
00:20:54,820 --> 00:20:56,082
This is Bunyan Pritchett speaking.

373
00:20:56,154 --> 00:20:57,086
This is Winthrop Zimmerman.

374
00:20:57,155 --> 00:20:58,053
This is Calver Weems.

375
00:20:58,123 --> 00:20:59,317
Nestor Pomerantz.

376
00:20:59,391 --> 00:21:00,153
Riley Drubb speaking.

377
00:21:00,225 --> 00:21:07,461
But in 1976, ABC television broadcast
a show which profoundly moved us all.

378
00:21:08,166 --> 00:21:09,463
Alex Haley's 'Roots.'

379
00:21:10,769 --> 00:21:12,634
Inspiration overcame us,

380
00:21:12,738 --> 00:21:16,799
and we agreed to honor our ancestors
by returning to our original names.

381
00:21:17,876 --> 00:21:19,537
This is Bunyan Pritchett speaking.

382
00:21:20,345 --> 00:21:22,575
And you tried the first?
Nonsense.

383
00:21:22,681 --> 00:21:24,308
Happy Garfield, everyone.

384
00:21:24,716 --> 00:21:25,978
Happy Garfield

385
00:21:26,051 --> 00:21:27,780
And Henry,
Turner would like to see us.

386
00:21:28,854 --> 00:21:32,551
Rebecca, Henry.
Like you to meet Pearl Stricklett.

387
00:21:32,624 --> 00:21:34,251
You're with Landry Ventures?

388
00:21:34,359 --> 00:21:37,192
No, lord no.
She's Mike's replacement.

389
00:21:37,429 --> 00:21:38,191
She, she's what?

390
00:21:38,363 --> 00:21:41,196
Mike's replacement.
You know, dead Mike.

391
00:21:41,266 --> 00:21:42,756
Oh, it was a heart attack?

392
00:21:42,834 --> 00:21:43,425
Stake.

393
00:21:43,969 --> 00:21:44,401
Stake?

394
00:21:44,469 --> 00:21:44,958
Stake.

395
00:21:45,037 --> 00:21:47,801
Steak. Red meat. Stuff will kill you.

396
00:21:48,273 --> 00:21:50,400
I thought we were going to
promote from, uh, within, Turner.

397
00:21:50,475 --> 00:21:51,908
You didn't get the memo?

398
00:21:52,077 --> 00:21:52,771
No.

399
00:21:53,011 --> 00:21:54,780
I guess I'll have to write one, then.

400
00:21:54,780 --> 00:21:58,716
You see, we need fresh blood,
fresh approaches. New ideas.

401
00:21:59,151 --> 00:22:01,984
You got some pretty big shoes to fill,
there, Pearl.

402
00:22:02,054 --> 00:22:05,546
Mike Yarrow did some quality work
for us, but he's dead.

403
00:22:05,857 --> 00:22:08,553
So I guess
that lowers the bar somewhat.

404
00:22:09,895 --> 00:22:13,194
You can't expect much
from a dead guy.

405
00:22:20,305 --> 00:22:21,932
You know, there's no need to panic.

406
00:22:23,008 --> 00:22:26,535
I mean, company policy gives her
two weeks probation,

407
00:22:27,145 --> 00:22:29,136
after that we can find some way
to get rid of her.

408
00:22:31,149 --> 00:22:32,673
This week's not going well, Henry.

409
00:22:33,151 --> 00:22:34,413
Turner's slipping fast.

410
00:22:35,387 --> 00:22:39,187
Is it,
is it time to consider the Rinse?

411
00:22:39,558 --> 00:22:43,756
Dr. Berman devised
the Remedial Rinse about 30 years ago.

412
00:22:44,096 --> 00:22:45,825
It's a crude technique whereby

413
00:22:45,897 --> 00:22:49,492
enzymatic fluid is flushed through
the victim's cerebral cortex.

414
00:22:49,968 --> 00:22:51,629
It stimulates those portions
of the brain

415
00:22:51,703 --> 00:22:54,695
that retardation's rendered lost
or unresponsive.

416
00:22:55,140 --> 00:22:58,735
The method works well, however
it carries with it a huge risk.

417
00:22:59,311 --> 00:23:02,041
The victim's brain
will likely die completely,

418
00:23:02,814 --> 00:23:05,282
so the Remedial Rinse brings
fleeting clarity,

419
00:23:05,350 --> 00:23:08,217
and nine times out of ten,
certain death.

420
00:23:09,721 --> 00:23:11,382
We use it only if we have to.

421
00:23:13,291 --> 00:23:15,657
Morning Otto, are we winning?

422
00:23:16,194 --> 00:23:16,888
Excuse me?

423
00:23:16,962 --> 00:23:17,986
I said, are we winning?

424
00:23:18,630 --> 00:23:21,656
Uh, yeah,
we're hitting it and getting it.

425
00:23:21,733 --> 00:23:25,396
Aces. Pearl Stricklett,
I'd like you to meet Otto Granberry.

426
00:23:25,470 --> 00:23:27,938
He's going to put you through
the systems 'til you get up to speed.

427
00:23:28,006 --> 00:23:29,701
You can use her, right?

428
00:23:29,775 --> 00:23:31,675
Oh, yeah, I'll use her.

429
00:23:32,344 --> 00:23:36,041
Her skills, her business skills.

430
00:23:36,681 --> 00:23:37,409
Hi.

431
00:23:39,017 --> 00:23:40,314
It's nice to meet you, Pearl.

432
00:23:41,453 --> 00:23:42,477
Mr. Claymore.

433
00:23:43,321 --> 00:23:46,688
Um, Turner says
you're quite the systems guru.

434
00:23:47,058 --> 00:23:48,685
Oh, I don't,
I don't know about a guru.

435
00:23:48,760 --> 00:23:51,194
No, come on, Otto. You're a guru.

436
00:23:51,530 --> 00:23:53,555
I just hope
you'll be patient with me.

437
00:23:53,632 --> 00:23:55,361
He's a guru. Patience.

438
00:23:56,401 --> 00:23:57,629
I've got all the time in the world.

439
00:23:59,137 --> 00:24:00,468
So what's the occasion?

440
00:24:00,839 --> 00:24:02,534
It's Garfield's birthday.

441
00:24:03,375 --> 00:24:05,002
Oh. Who's Garfield?

442
00:24:05,577 --> 00:24:06,635
Him.

443
00:24:07,813 --> 00:24:10,748
President Garfield? Seriously?

444
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:14,912
The primary reason that Berm-Tech
exists is due to James Garfield.

445
00:24:15,887 --> 00:24:19,414
A man named Charles Guiteau
discovered Garfield was one of us

446
00:24:19,491 --> 00:24:21,393
and tried to blackmail him.

447
00:24:21,393 --> 00:24:26,330
When Garfield refused, Guiteau decided
to expose him in a very obvious way.

448
00:24:26,398 --> 00:24:27,023
He shot him.

449
00:24:28,733 --> 00:24:30,963
Alexander Graham Bell DR.

450
00:24:31,503 --> 00:24:33,528
Mr. Bell, I'm Dr. Berman.

451
00:24:34,406 --> 00:24:35,566
The President thanks you.

452
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:37,733
Well he can thank me
himself once I've saved his life.

453
00:24:40,412 --> 00:24:42,710
But Bell was not brought in
to save the President,

454
00:24:42,781 --> 00:24:45,417
as Garfield would have,
obviously, survived.

455
00:24:45,417 --> 00:24:49,285
All Bell needed to do was locate
the bullet with his newest invention,

456
00:24:49,488 --> 00:24:50,477
the metal detector.

457
00:24:51,089 --> 00:24:53,649
But for all his talent,
and arrogance, Bell,

458
00:24:54,125 --> 00:24:56,059
the greatest mechanical mind
of the century,

459
00:24:56,261 --> 00:24:57,193
couldn't find the bullet.

460
00:24:57,696 --> 00:25:01,325
This was due to another new invention,
the metal box spring.

461
00:25:02,934 --> 00:25:05,334
This was of little consolation
to Bell.

462
00:25:06,037 --> 00:25:08,130
His failure only underscored the fact

463
00:25:08,206 --> 00:25:11,539
that there was something wholly
unnatural about the President.

464
00:25:12,711 --> 00:25:15,179
I see the surgeons watching me, Myron.

465
00:25:17,782 --> 00:25:19,249
They know, don't they?

466
00:25:20,118 --> 00:25:21,642
Your wounds are healing too quickly.

467
00:25:21,786 --> 00:25:24,414
There are too
many unanswered questions being asked.

468
00:25:25,156 --> 00:25:29,820
I'm sorry, my friend, they will not
have a monster as Commander-in-Chief.

469
00:25:30,095 --> 00:25:33,326
Perhaps it is time to enjoin you into
that greater number.

470
00:25:33,798 --> 00:25:41,261
I would ask that you permit time to
try to bring the good from our anomaly.

471
00:25:41,740 --> 00:25:43,970
After the sacrifice
President Garfield made,

472
00:25:44,042 --> 00:25:47,034
Bell and Dr. Berman knew they needed
to create a safe haven for us.

473
00:25:47,512 --> 00:25:50,242
Thus, Berm-Tech industries was born.

474
00:25:52,417 --> 00:25:56,820
Berm-Tech has been around
for a very long time,

475
00:25:57,522 --> 00:25:59,547
so you must be doing something right.

476
00:26:00,425 --> 00:26:04,293
I think it's because
of your patience.

477
00:26:05,330 --> 00:26:10,131
As the saying goes,
'slow and steady wins the race.'

478
00:26:13,872 --> 00:26:15,567
Yes, Cecil?

479
00:26:16,241 --> 00:26:17,367
I'm Amos, that's Cecil.

480
00:26:17,676 --> 00:26:22,579
It's, um, I'm not sure, uh, I've
ever truly understood that statement,

481
00:26:22,647 --> 00:26:24,547
uh, 'slow and steady wins the race.'

482
00:26:24,616 --> 00:26:26,174
I mean, patience is a virtue,

483
00:26:26,418 --> 00:26:28,113
uh, yes, but I, I don't think it...

484
00:26:28,186 --> 00:26:29,585
It's from
'The Tortoise and the Hare,' Amos.

485
00:26:29,654 --> 00:26:30,621
I know what it's from, Cecil,

486
00:26:30,689 --> 00:26:32,213
I didn't just fall off
the turnip truck.

487
00:26:32,290 --> 00:26:35,316
The thing is, that particular story is
a lousy illustration of Steven's point.

488
00:26:35,393 --> 00:26:37,759
No, it's the whole point of
the damn story, Amos.

489
00:26:37,829 --> 00:26:41,321
Feel free to jump in here, Steven,
if I'm talking out of my hat.

490
00:26:41,433 --> 00:26:43,526
Listen, in a nutshell, Amos,

491
00:26:43,602 --> 00:26:46,765
the slow tortoise,
an underdog if ever there was one,

492
00:26:46,838 --> 00:26:49,033
ends up beating the rabbit
to the finish line

493
00:26:49,107 --> 00:26:52,008
because he was slow and steady.

494
00:26:52,077 --> 00:26:55,444
No, he beat the rabbit because
the rabbit was teasing the tortoise.

495
00:26:55,513 --> 00:26:58,812
And, and, and taking naps and
showing off to all the other animals,

496
00:26:58,883 --> 00:26:59,815
and carrying on and the like.

497
00:26:59,884 --> 00:27:02,444
It had virtually nothing to do
with the pace of the tortoise.

498
00:27:02,554 --> 00:27:06,354
The tortoise won because the,
the rabbit was an asshole.

499
00:27:07,158 --> 00:27:08,989
You don't even know that rabbit.

500
00:27:12,330 --> 00:27:16,994
People, please, let's not turn this
into a blame-storming session.

501
00:27:17,068 --> 00:27:21,402
Maybe I should, um,
give more thought to my analogies.

502
00:27:21,473 --> 00:27:25,136
Nonsense, your analogy
was charming and bittersweet.

503
00:27:25,377 --> 00:27:28,778
I think what Steven's trying
to convey with his analogy

504
00:27:28,847 --> 00:27:31,714
is that even though there were
any number of contributing factors

505
00:27:31,783 --> 00:27:34,217
which lead to the tortoise
being named the victor,

506
00:27:34,285 --> 00:27:36,310
poor sportsmanship
and narcolepsy among them,

507
00:27:36,388 --> 00:27:40,882
the fact remains that the turtle
methodically continued his progress

508
00:27:40,959 --> 00:27:43,291
until he reached his goal.

509
00:27:43,528 --> 00:27:47,897
Even though the rabbit
clearly should have won.

510
00:27:48,500 --> 00:27:51,333
Much faster than a tortoise.

511
00:27:52,704 --> 00:27:57,403
Or the, or the tortoise
in this thing, anyway.

512
00:27:57,575 --> 00:27:58,667
Yes.

513
00:27:59,310 --> 00:28:02,973
Wow, I can't get over
how elaborate this place is.

514
00:28:03,481 --> 00:28:04,607
It's like a real restaurant.

515
00:28:05,016 --> 00:28:09,919
Yeah. Well the, uh, hourly employees
have a really strong union.

516
00:28:10,321 --> 00:28:13,916
Ah, the new employee. Welcome.

517
00:28:14,826 --> 00:28:17,852
Would you like the special?
Uh, pot pie today.

518
00:28:18,530 --> 00:28:21,465
Oh, pot pie. Yeah. Uh, what's in it?

519
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:24,795
Nothing but good stuff,
I promise you that.

520
00:28:26,938 --> 00:28:27,927
"No Human Flesh."

521
00:28:28,006 --> 00:28:31,066
I'll take your word for it.
Thank you.

522
00:28:33,111 --> 00:28:33,736
You're welcome.

523
00:28:37,449 --> 00:28:38,609
Can I get you a salad?

524
00:28:39,017 --> 00:28:43,249
Yes, please. Uh, what kind of
salad dressing do you have?

525
00:28:43,822 --> 00:28:46,791
Pretty much anything.
Got about a dozen different kinds.

526
00:28:47,392 --> 00:28:51,158
Oh, wow, okay.
Um, how about creamy garlic?

527
00:28:53,798 --> 00:28:56,289
Yeah, see garlic is a tricky thing.

528
00:28:56,634 --> 00:28:57,760
Aversion to garlic.

529
00:28:57,836 --> 00:28:59,531
Okay, there's some truth to that one.

530
00:29:00,004 --> 00:29:03,565
Not all types of garlic,
but some of the hardneck varieties,

531
00:29:03,641 --> 00:29:07,975
like Rocambole and Chesnok Red
are extremely toxic to Nether Folk.

532
00:29:08,847 --> 00:29:11,645
Franklin Abercrombie found
that out the hard way

533
00:29:11,716 --> 00:29:14,708
when he snuck in a plate of
shrimp scampi back in 1958.

534
00:29:23,928 --> 00:29:25,589
Hi, mind if we sit here?

535
00:29:26,097 --> 00:29:27,223
Sure.

536
00:29:28,166 --> 00:29:29,724
I hope we didn't interrupt anything.

537
00:29:29,801 --> 00:29:32,235
Not at all. We're just discussing
Dow's bad habits.

538
00:29:32,904 --> 00:29:35,134
Not exactly good meal time talk.

539
00:29:35,340 --> 00:29:38,543
I have a strong stomach,
so don't let me interrupt.

540
00:29:38,543 --> 00:29:40,477
We've already covered
the real vile ones.

541
00:29:40,545 --> 00:29:42,672
Uh, nose picking, throat snorting.

542
00:29:42,747 --> 00:29:43,907
Testicle scratching.

543
00:29:43,982 --> 00:29:46,017
Okay,
maybe we should sit somewhere else.

544
00:29:46,017 --> 00:29:47,041
Back me up here, Pearl.

545
00:29:47,118 --> 00:29:49,450
These men, it's always scratch,
scratch, scratch. Am I right?

546
00:29:50,989 --> 00:29:52,581
No, Jewel, you're not right.

547
00:29:52,991 --> 00:29:55,186
It's never scratch, scratch, scratch.
That's a myth.

548
00:29:56,060 --> 00:29:59,518
Oh, please, Dow.
And I suppose men don't scratch?

549
00:29:59,697 --> 00:30:01,597
No, technically we do not.

550
00:30:01,666 --> 00:30:03,224
Not down in the testicular region.

551
00:30:03,301 --> 00:30:04,199
Jeff's right.

552
00:30:04,502 --> 00:30:08,165
From an engineering standpoint,
the scrotum is a complete disaster.

553
00:30:08,907 --> 00:30:12,274
See, the Good Lord designed
the scrotum in such a way

554
00:30:12,443 --> 00:30:15,708
to make it inefficient
to simply scratch away at it.

555
00:30:15,914 --> 00:30:18,474
It's like,
uh, chopping wood on a waterbed.

556
00:30:18,550 --> 00:30:20,279
It lacks stability and rigidity.

557
00:30:20,819 --> 00:30:25,188
So there are two preferred methods
that can be employed to scratch,

558
00:30:25,256 --> 00:30:26,985
if you will, your nether regions.

559
00:30:27,058 --> 00:30:28,923
I'm more of a pinch and roll man,
myself.

560
00:30:29,427 --> 00:30:30,758
Yeah,
and I prefer the stretch and flick.

561
00:30:30,895 --> 00:30:33,193
The stretch and flick.

562
00:30:34,899 --> 00:30:37,868
I, uh,
saw Emmitt in the lounge last night.

563
00:30:39,037 --> 00:30:41,198
That must have been shortly
after we checked his room.

564
00:30:41,539 --> 00:30:44,940
He took a bunch of stuff with him.
Mostly clothes.

565
00:30:46,477 --> 00:30:47,842
Why would he absquatulate?

566
00:30:48,680 --> 00:30:50,739
Maybe he found another source
of Nether Stone.

567
00:30:52,483 --> 00:30:53,541
Did he seem moody?

568
00:30:54,953 --> 00:30:55,851
Not at all.

569
00:30:56,087 --> 00:30:58,851
In fact, he and Judd Plimmer
were laughing and making merry

570
00:30:58,923 --> 00:31:04,088
and having some sort of contest
that involved, well, pooting.

571
00:31:04,662 --> 00:31:06,857
See? What, what did I tell you
about those sloppy Joes? Hmm?

572
00:31:09,801 --> 00:31:10,631
Okay, I'm off.

573
00:31:11,002 --> 00:31:13,334
Thanks a lot for all your help today.

574
00:31:13,404 --> 00:31:16,464
I know this can be
really overwhelming.

575
00:31:17,141 --> 00:31:20,440
No, it's the best way to learn,
falling into it.

576
00:31:22,080 --> 00:31:23,911
So, it seems like a fun group.

577
00:31:25,016 --> 00:31:28,918
And with the Garfield cake
and the testicular engineering.

578
00:31:29,053 --> 00:31:31,214
Don't worry,
it's not always like that.

579
00:31:31,289 --> 00:31:33,052
Damn, I was hoping it was.

580
00:31:34,993 --> 00:31:38,224
Um, so are, are you leaving soon,
Otto?

581
00:31:38,630 --> 00:31:41,394
Yeah. In a little bit, yeah.

582
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:44,097
Do you guys ever do happy hour?

583
00:31:46,871 --> 00:31:48,498
I thought maybe we could grab a drink.

584
00:31:51,943 --> 00:31:52,932
Or some coffee.

585
00:31:53,444 --> 00:31:54,672
Uh, I...

586
00:31:54,746 --> 00:31:56,646
I mean, unless you have a,
a wife to get home to.

587
00:31:57,615 --> 00:32:01,244
Or you have something else to do,
or something.

588
00:32:01,619 --> 00:32:07,023
I, I don't have a wife,
but I have a dog.

589
00:32:07,859 --> 00:32:08,621
Oh, you have a dog?

590
00:32:08,693 --> 00:32:09,387
Yeah.

591
00:32:10,161 --> 00:32:11,219
What's his name?

592
00:32:11,462 --> 00:32:15,660
His name? His, his name is Jeeves.

593
00:32:16,100 --> 00:32:16,498
Jeeves?

594
00:32:16,567 --> 00:32:17,329
Yeah.

595
00:32:18,569 --> 00:32:19,797
That's cute.

596
00:32:19,871 --> 00:32:20,496
Yeah.

597
00:32:22,240 --> 00:32:23,400
Maybe another time?

598
00:32:24,442 --> 00:32:27,343
Yeah. Yeah, absolutely.

599
00:32:27,712 --> 00:32:28,371
Maybe another time?

600
00:32:28,646 --> 00:32:30,375
What other time you talkin' about?

601
00:32:30,448 --> 00:32:32,143
When are you ever going out
for a drink?

602
00:32:32,417 --> 00:32:34,578
I don't know.
Maybe if it was later in the evening?

603
00:32:36,988 --> 00:32:37,750
Like Monday night?

604
00:32:40,792 --> 00:32:43,386
Wait a second.
I know what you're talking about,

605
00:32:43,461 --> 00:32:45,622
you're talking about misusing
Purveyance Night, aren't you?

606
00:32:46,397 --> 00:32:47,022
Maybe.

607
00:32:47,432 --> 00:32:50,196
Purveyance Night is our sole
opportunity to get out of the building,

608
00:32:50,268 --> 00:32:52,930
to do some personal shopping
or what have you.

609
00:32:53,371 --> 00:32:56,397
Each employee's rotation comes up
every seven weeks or so.

610
00:32:56,908 --> 00:32:59,376
Which leads into the question of...

611
00:32:59,444 --> 00:33:00,911
Can't go out in the sunlight.

612
00:33:01,312 --> 00:33:02,677
Not entirely true.

613
00:33:02,947 --> 00:33:04,209
Yes, it's harmful,

614
00:33:04,349 --> 00:33:07,750
but not quite to the degree
the movies would have you believe.

615
00:33:08,286 --> 00:33:10,186
In the early days
we'd go out periodically,

616
00:33:10,254 --> 00:33:13,314
but it was easier to protect your
skin back when hats were in vogue.

617
00:33:13,925 --> 00:33:16,485
We did a lot of damage
to our bones in those days.

618
00:33:16,995 --> 00:33:22,433
We didn't realize how much until Amos
Crenshaw's 120th birthday party in 1950.

619
00:33:22,700 --> 00:33:26,067
After that, Turner kept Berm-Tech
locked up tighter than Dick's hat band.

620
00:33:26,904 --> 00:33:30,169
But this only succeeded in
pissing everyone off to the point

621
00:33:30,241 --> 00:33:31,674
where we felt like prisoners.

622
00:33:32,710 --> 00:33:37,613
All of this culminated in the
Great Worker Rebellion of 1981,

623
00:33:37,682 --> 00:33:39,843
documented in this black
velvet painting.

624
00:33:40,518 --> 00:33:44,249
That's when Turner proposed the current
Purveyance Night rotational system.

625
00:33:45,156 --> 00:33:46,748
You're not scheduled
for Monday night.

626
00:33:47,625 --> 00:33:48,284
No?

627
00:33:48,559 --> 00:33:49,787
You going to just let me shoot it?

628
00:33:51,129 --> 00:33:52,118
But you are.

629
00:33:53,097 --> 00:33:54,655
Come on, Otto,
I don't want to switch.

630
00:33:56,467 --> 00:33:58,025
Ask Elton or Monroe.

631
00:33:58,903 --> 00:34:01,030
Sweeten the pot,
I bet you Monroe will do it.

632
00:34:02,573 --> 00:34:05,041
It's true. He likes good wine.

633
00:34:05,243 --> 00:34:07,336
He does. He does.

634
00:34:08,980 --> 00:34:10,345
He loves the wine.

635
00:34:11,115 --> 00:34:14,778
You know what I love?
I love slam-dunking in your face!

636
00:34:20,925 --> 00:34:25,259
Well, I'm not doing this for me, Waxy.
I'm doing this for Berm-Tech.

637
00:34:25,963 --> 00:34:30,400
That's ludicrous. How is bringing her
out for a drink going to help Berm-Tech?

638
00:34:30,501 --> 00:34:33,766
Well, she'll leave here thinking
this is a normal company,

639
00:34:33,838 --> 00:34:36,568
the kind where the employees
occasionally leave the building.

640
00:34:36,874 --> 00:34:39,502
What could be more normal
than going out for happy hour?

641
00:34:39,577 --> 00:34:44,480
Oh, uh, that makes total sense.
You're so smart.

642
00:34:47,852 --> 00:34:50,548
Just tell her you have family commitments,
and be as vague as you like.

643
00:34:50,621 --> 00:34:51,610
She ain't gonna pry.

644
00:34:52,090 --> 00:34:55,116
It's kind of hard to break up with
someone you're not even dating, Waxy.

645
00:34:55,359 --> 00:34:55,825
And when you tell her,

646
00:34:55,893 --> 00:34:58,987
look her right in the eye and
give her the Eye of the Jackal.

647
00:34:59,730 --> 00:35:02,597
The Eye of the Jackal?
What the hell is that?

648
00:35:03,734 --> 00:35:08,603
Listen, Otto, the Eye of the Jackal.
It's the only way.

649
00:35:09,974 --> 00:35:11,601
Yeah, but what am I supposed to...

650
00:35:11,676 --> 00:35:13,644
The Eye of the Jackal, sir.

651
00:35:16,380 --> 00:35:17,312
Look at that.

652
00:35:20,651 --> 00:35:22,676
Have you seen
how big my shoulders are getting?

653
00:35:41,372 --> 00:35:42,896
Kitchen's closed.

654
00:35:43,407 --> 00:35:44,704
You know the rules.

655
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:54,641
So, yeah, then you just do
the same thing for the next...

656
00:35:54,719 --> 00:35:55,845
Monday started very well,

657
00:35:56,053 --> 00:35:58,044
in spite of the fact
that it was Monday.

658
00:35:58,389 --> 00:36:01,017
I'd popped the big happy hour
question at around eight-fifteen.

659
00:36:01,559 --> 00:36:03,686
And of course,
the answer was affirmative.

660
00:36:04,095 --> 00:36:05,426
I felt pretty good about that.

661
00:36:06,597 --> 00:36:08,064
Hey, listen, Granberry,

662
00:36:08,132 --> 00:36:10,123
I was wondering, uh, if maybe you
and I could get together,

663
00:36:10,201 --> 00:36:11,600
have a little intercourse
before lunch?

664
00:36:11,869 --> 00:36:14,861
Possible?
Any time before eleven-thirty.

665
00:36:15,473 --> 00:36:16,405
Hi.

666
00:36:18,242 --> 00:36:20,335
I hid from Steven for
the rest of the day.

667
00:36:22,313 --> 00:36:23,575
Myrtie Vanhoover?

668
00:36:23,648 --> 00:36:26,014
Yep. She's never been late.

669
00:36:26,884 --> 00:36:29,114
I checked her room
and a lot of her stuff is gone.

670
00:36:29,520 --> 00:36:31,283
Did she seem unhappy at all?

671
00:36:32,056 --> 00:36:36,356
The whole kitchen staff has been unhappy
since that first lifer, Pearl, was hired.

672
00:36:36,427 --> 00:36:36,984
But Monroe, you...

673
00:36:37,061 --> 00:36:38,392
But, but, but, but.

674
00:36:38,729 --> 00:36:42,756
Some of my crew
have been waiting 15, 20 years

675
00:36:42,833 --> 00:36:44,596
for their white collar rotation.

676
00:36:45,603 --> 00:36:48,470
Same thing happened
with Mike Yarrow last year

677
00:36:48,539 --> 00:36:50,200
when he got preferential treatment.

678
00:36:50,474 --> 00:36:53,136
Yeah,
but you saw what happened to him.

679
00:36:53,211 --> 00:36:57,580
Yeah, but, uh, perhaps my kitchen staff
is capable of writing an initiative

680
00:36:57,648 --> 00:36:59,843
that won't result in death.

681
00:37:00,885 --> 00:37:01,852
Duly noted?

682
00:37:03,120 --> 00:37:04,678
Uh, duly noted. Duly noted.

683
00:37:10,561 --> 00:37:15,498
Now, do, do we know
if Emmitt and Myrtie were,

684
00:37:16,667 --> 00:37:17,656
you know...

685
00:37:20,771 --> 00:37:21,965
I don't think so.

686
00:37:22,273 --> 00:37:23,240
We need to consider

687
00:37:23,307 --> 00:37:26,037
that another source of Nether Stone
has been found in the city.

688
00:37:26,844 --> 00:37:30,041
Well we also need to consider
company-wide bonuses as well.

689
00:37:36,721 --> 00:37:38,416
It's been nice working with you.

690
00:37:50,635 --> 00:37:54,264
Is something wrong with this door,
or something?

691
00:37:55,373 --> 00:37:56,397
Is there something wrong with it,
June?

692
00:37:56,474 --> 00:37:58,965
It's Jewel, sir,
and the door's fine, Mr. Claymore.

693
00:37:59,043 --> 00:38:01,978
If there's nothing wrong with this
door, then why can't I get it open?

694
00:38:02,046 --> 00:38:03,411
Has it been repurposed or something?

695
00:38:03,481 --> 00:38:05,415
Is that what's been
going on around here?

696
00:38:05,483 --> 00:38:08,077
Because I can understand a modicum
of monkey business in the workplace

697
00:38:08,152 --> 00:38:10,416
to sort of boost morale,
but really you...

698
00:38:10,488 --> 00:38:12,115
I'm not sure
where he thought home was,

699
00:38:12,189 --> 00:38:14,214
but he was determined to get there.

700
00:38:20,464 --> 00:38:24,730
Sure, I can keep him sedated 24 hours
a day if that's what you want.

701
00:38:24,835 --> 00:38:28,168
But the retardations can't reverse
themselves under those conditions.

702
00:38:28,406 --> 00:38:31,933
In that case, we might
as well do the Remedial Rinse.

703
00:38:32,109 --> 00:38:35,078
I tell you, everything would be
a whole lot easier with the Rinse.

704
00:38:35,946 --> 00:38:38,176
We can't lose sight at
what's at stake, Henry.

705
00:38:38,916 --> 00:38:41,578
What would Turner do
if you two switched places?

706
00:38:41,786 --> 00:38:44,619
What if we were just
to sedate him at night? After work.

707
00:38:45,723 --> 00:38:48,817
Okay, here's the deal,
mark his calendar with meetings,

708
00:38:48,893 --> 00:38:51,123
have two guys shadow him at all times.

709
00:38:51,762 --> 00:38:54,754
But the moment the workday ends,
we're knocking him out.

710
00:38:56,534 --> 00:38:58,058
It's eight-fifty now.

711
00:38:59,270 --> 00:39:02,068
Alright, ladies, we have three hours,
let's make the most of it.

712
00:39:02,139 --> 00:39:05,131
So Waxy, Jewel,
Elton and I left for Purveyance Night.

713
00:39:05,209 --> 00:39:05,800
Let's go.

714
00:39:05,876 --> 00:39:08,003
Oh, I guess I should explain
the whole Elton thing.

715
00:39:08,713 --> 00:39:12,513
See, back in 1976
when we were all watching 'Roots,'

716
00:39:13,084 --> 00:39:17,953
Walter Shackleford was in another room
watching an episode of Merv Griffin...

717
00:39:18,022 --> 00:39:20,616
...featuring, well, Elton John.

718
00:39:22,126 --> 00:39:23,650
And he hasn't spoken since.

719
00:39:29,233 --> 00:39:30,393
She seems very sweet, Otto,

720
00:39:30,468 --> 00:39:32,527
but I don't know
how to talk to a modern woman.

721
00:39:32,636 --> 00:39:33,694
We have nothing in common.

722
00:39:34,004 --> 00:39:35,062
Well, you're both female.

723
00:39:35,473 --> 00:39:37,407
You could talk about things
that are inherently female.

724
00:39:38,476 --> 00:39:39,465
Alright, I'll give it a try.

725
00:39:39,777 --> 00:39:41,768
Otto, we need to go.

726
00:39:41,846 --> 00:39:45,282
Hey, if you two lovebirds want to waste
your time prowling for wine, be my guest.

727
00:39:45,349 --> 00:39:49,547
Elton and I are going to a movie.
Good luck.

728
00:39:54,959 --> 00:39:56,893
Okay, there she is.

729
00:39:57,495 --> 00:39:58,427
Now about the wine...

730
00:39:58,496 --> 00:39:59,656
Relax, I'll take care of it.

731
00:39:59,730 --> 00:40:01,425
Go have fun, let her down easy,

732
00:40:01,499 --> 00:40:04,024
and above all, Eye of the Jackal.

733
00:40:05,236 --> 00:40:06,533
You know, I'm still not completely...

734
